   pfur@iol.ie  
   
   




@endnode

@node "CHORDS" "CHORDS"
@next "COPY"
@prev "Descriptions"
@{fg highlight} 
                                  
                                  CHORDS@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/chords.iff/MAIN" 0}   


   Enter the root note in the editor page, and use a macro to create 
   a chord.
   
   Here is the list of chords available, each one a separate macro.
@{fg Highlight}
AUG NINTH(9+)
AUG TRIAD(+)
AUG TRIAD(+)    
DIM TRIAD(o)
ELEVENTH FLAT NINTH 
ELEVENTH
m(+5)                      
m(MAJ7)
MAJOR NINTH  
MAJOR SEVENTH      
MAJOR              
MAJORTRIAD         
minor
minor ninth         
minor seventh      
minor sixth
minortriad       
NINTH AUG ELEVENTH 
NINTH              
o(MAJ7)            
o7                 
SEVENTH FLAT FIFTH 
SEVENTH FLAT NINTH 
SEVENTH SUS4       
SEVENTH
SIXTH        
SUS4
THIRTEENTH AUG ELEV   
THIRTEENTH FLAT NINTH
THIRTEENTH  
ř
@{fg text}


@endnode








@node "COPY" "COPY"
@next "ECHO"
@prev "CHORDS"
@{fg highlight}  
                                    
                               COPY@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/copy.iff/MAIN" 0}

   Use this macro to copy either selected notes, or a marked region. Will 
   copy any number of bars up to 99 times and automatically paste them at 
   the end of the marked region, or selected events. This macro is 
   particularly good for copying short patterns throughout a song,ie 
   extending a few bars of drums to become the drum track for a song. 
   

   I know that the Music-x's repeat function fills a similar role, but 
   your song doesn't translate very well into a midi file if you use that. 
   With this macro, the repeats are actually written to the track.
   
   
   If the selected notes or marked region that you want to copy does not
   exceed 4 beats, then @{"ECHO" link "ECHO" 0} will do the job a bit faster.
@endnode

@node "ECHO" "ECHO"
@next "FLIP"
@prev "COPY"
@{fg highlight}
               
                                   ECHO@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/echo.iff/MAIN" 0}

   Creates echos of selected notes. Also works properly with marked areas.
   Can have falling or ascending attack velocities, or keep the same level 
   of attack as the selected notes. In this version, delays can be up to
   4 beats, ie one bar of 4/4 time.

   
   If you keep the attack velocity level, and the selected notes or marked 
   region to 4 beats or under, then this macro is actually faster at
   copying than the @{"COPY" link "COPY" 0} one.  
 
   
@endnode

@node "FLIP" "FLIP"
@next "INVERT"
@prev "ECHO"
@{fg highlight}
               
                                   FLIP@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/flip.iff/MAIN" 0}

   Flips events around an axis. Turns a tune upside down. Can render a
   good tune senseless, but you might enjoy using this macro. 

   
   @{u}Works for marked area@{uu} when `selected' is chosen.

@endnode


@node "INVERT" "INVERT"
@next "LOGICALSELECT"
@prev "FLIP"
@{fg highlight}
               
                                  INVERT@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/invert.iff/MAIN" 0}

   This is useful if like me, you are not a wonderful keyboard player.
   Different inversions of chords can be obtained by defining the upper 
   and lower limits of the notes that you have played. This macro will
   move the notes to their new positions within the range that you have 
   defined. 

   
   @{u}Works for marked area@{uu} when `selected' is chosen.



@endnode


@node "LOGICALSELECT" "LOGICALSELECT"
@next "REVERSE"
@prev "INVERT"
@{fg highlight}    
               
                               LOGICALSELECT@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/logsel.iff/MAIN" 0}


   This one fills the gap left in the Logical Select module supplied with 
   Music-x 2.0. It allows you to select events time-wise in each bar. For
   example, if you have a hundred bars of drums with one annoying hi-hat
   landing around the middle of the third beat in each bar, it can be very
   time consuming to manually select or delete each individual event. This 
   macro allows you to painlessly select that event in each bar. You can 
   select as wide a time span as you want within the bar, or define it to 
   the exact clock. Used in conjunctio with Music-x's own Logical Select 
   module, it should now be possible to logically select any events. 

   
   @{u}This macro also works on marked sections@{uu}.
   

   I have limited the number of beats in the bar to 8 in this version. If
   anyone has need of a version to work with a larger number of beats they 
   can contact me through the address on the @{"Last Word" link "Last Word" 0} page.
   


@endnode

@node "REVERSE" "REVERSE"
@next "Last Word"
@prev "LOGICALSELECT"
@{fg highlight}
               
                                  REVERSE@{fg text}        @{"Screenshot" link "pics/reverse.iff/MAIN" 0}


   This macro, surprisingly enough, reverses selected notes. Turns a tune 
   backwards. Another way, along with @{"FLIP" link "FLIP" 0} to ruin a good tune. Good fun, 
   if not positively inspiring. 


   The results are erratic when used with a marked area, so stick to 
   @{u}selected notes@{uu} with this one.


   If there are events other than notes selected, the macro will probably
   fail.




@endnode


